SIMPLE: myth
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Myth
<hw>Myth</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>mythe</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my^qos</grk> myth, fable,
tale, talk, speech: cf. F. <ets>mythe</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
story of great but unknown age which originally embodied a belief
regarding some fact or phenomenon of experience, and in which often the
forces of nature and of the soul are personified; an ancient legend of a
god, a hero, the origin of a race, etc.; a wonder story of prehistoric
origin; a popular fable which is, or has been, received as
historical.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person or thing existing only in imagination, or
whose actual existence is not verifiable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As for Mrs. Primmins's bones, they had been <qex>myths</qex> these
twenty years.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Lytton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Myth history</b></col>, <cd>history made of, or mixed
with, myths.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythe</ent>⟦br⟧
